results.notes:
Physarum nutans Persoon description
Found 8/15/23, a colony of them on well-rotted wood in a log, in the woods near Lake Lemon IN.
Initial impression was small white “whiskers” on the wood. On closer examination, some of the white stalks had tiny gray sporangia which were oval shaped or flattened. Some had pointed white sporangia, and some had only an empty flat calyx; some of the stalks end in a bare stump.
Sporangia: 0.3 – 0.5 mm diameter; white then turning gray. Some of them nodding.
Stalks: Dull white, up to 2 mm long, 0.1 mm wide or less. Wider at the base, tapering to the top. Irregular contours, appearing rumpled; some with longitudinal furrows.
Calyx: appears flat or shallowly curved, as wide as the head but only at the base of the head.
Capillitium: smooth, clear, no spines or junctions, branching, appears to be net-like; 0.7 – 1.2 micron diameter. Many fusiform lime nodes, 18-30 × 9-19 microns.
Peridium: contains clumps of lime; irregular patches, not a continuous membrane.
Spores: Light brown by transmitted light. Round, minutely spinulose (only barely visible at 1000x) and with a reticulum (also only apparent at 1000x, by photographing slightly out of focus). 8.2 – 9.3 microns.
results.location_name: Lake Lemon, Brown Co., Indiana, USA

results.notes:
Tiny orange cup fungus description
Found 8-15-23, several of them growing on leaf stems (oak leaves and other), in the duff of a hollow log. In the woods near Lake Lemon, Brown County, IN.
Caps: Bright orange, largest is about 1.5 mm diameter. A shallow cup-shape, with edges somewhat scalloped; no obvious hairs or fringe on edges. Appears dry, not scaly. Outer sterile surface pale orange with some zoning; paler toward the center. Not hairy.
Stalk: wider at top, whitish at the top, dark brown at the base. About 1 mm long, 0.25 mm wide.
Microscopic: Spores are cylindrical with one end more pointed; smooth-walled with large oil droplets (one to two per spore). 17.2-23 × 4.4-5.9 microns.
Asci: Smooth-walled, colorless; most contain 8 spores. Not amyloid.

results.notes: Dotted around the gardens in various spots. a member of the “tough-skinned puffball” family, a group of mushrooms that are typically bulbous and puff-ball like in form but have a tough outer layer. Also distinctive is the stark contrast between this mushroom’s skin, usually a pale white or yellow color, and its inner spore tissue, which is nearly black. Onion earthballs are poisonous.

results.notes:
Description
Found 8/15/23, growing on wood in a well-rotted log, in the woods near Lake Lemon, IN. Five of them.
Caps: tan, plane, umbilicate with striate edges. Largest is 4 cm diameter. Smooth, not viscid or hygrophanous, although some of them developed paler radial streaks as they dried. No odor. KOH on cap: at first pale yellowish, then slowly turned dark orange-brown.
Gills: pale beige, forking near the stem, decurrent, close.
Stalk: Hollow; 0.5 cm wide, 3-4 cm long, rooting into the wood with a white mycelial pad, otherwise pale tan in the younger specimens (one with slightly pink tones); a bit darker with hint of lavender tones in the largest one. KOH on stalk turned very slowly dark brown.
Spore print: scanty; clear to white.
Spores: clear, smooth-walled, oval with slightly protruding apical pore and many small speckly intracellular organelles visible. 7.1-9.1 × 4.9-5.7 microns.
Staining reaction with Melzer’s: mildly amyloid.

results.notes:
Abortiporus biennis description
Found 8/17/23, growing in dirt next to tree roots at the edge of the woods, at Brown County Country Club disc golf course, Brown County, IN. A few clumps of them.
Fruiting bodies consist mostly of palisades of columns, covered in white pores, crowded together and arising from a common base. One of the clumps, however, has caps emerging from the columns along one side.
Pores: Variously shaped; on average about 2/mm. White, bruising tan. Covering the entire fruiting body except for the upper surface of the caps.
Caps: 3-4 cm wide; funnel-shaped, overall color is tan with some darker concentric zones (rust, brown) towards the edge. Central part of cap covered in fine light-beige fuzz. Edges are dark brown, sharp; rest of cap submerged in the pore surface. Tiny (1 mm diameter) white polyps scattered over surface of caps.
Columns: Up to 3.3 cm long, 1 cm wide although some are fused, up to 3 cm wide. Upright, coming to a blunt point. Covered in pores. Cut surface tan, with a lighter tan central pillar, 2 cm tall and 2 mm wide, inside each column. The pore layer is 4 mm deep. No change in color of the flesh with KOH.
Spore print: very faint, clear/white. Chalmydospores more common than spores.
Spores: elliptical, smooth walled, 6.2-7.5 × 4-4.7 microns.
Chlamydospores: spherical to broadly elliptical, smooth walled, 5.2-7.9 × 3.9-7.5 microns.
results.location_name: Brown Co., Indiana, USA
